gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0062"><gtr:id>5F33A799-1652-4516-A75C-512E26F552B8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Service Delivery to older people in Rural communities</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0062</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Devolution in Northern Ireland presents many challenges to policymakers. In Northern Ireland, the Office of the First and Deputy First Minister have stated their commitment to promote and support the inclusion of older people. It identified the need to deal with physical, attitudinal, information and affordability barriers that prevent older people from using services many in society take for granted. Rural areas and farming communities in particular are associated with certain cultural norms and expectations which may negatively impact their ability to access services. This is further compounded by increasing centralisation and rationalisation of services. This project aims to ensure that research-based evidence about the coherence, effectiveness, accessibility, impact and cost effectiveness of rural services informs policy development.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Using both qualitative and quantitative approaches the project aims to provide valuable information for future planning, provision and commissioning of services. The project will draw on and where appropriate undertake secondary analysis on existing quantitative sources to provide a contextual background. The qualitative approach will be largely based around in-depth interviews with older service users.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>65867</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Findings have been used:
- to inform government policy
- referred to by Patient Clkient Council and Older Peoples' Commissioner</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>C094D7EF-1531-440F-A354-37B7A44AAFF7</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>54634ad5d2c362.15425858</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Healthcare,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Research study concluded that; Older people are not a homogenous group which can be treated as a single entity, it is important to recognize that there are important variations with the older population and policies should be targeted at specific groups eg poor in health and those living alone. Family members, neighbours and community leaders play a significant role in providing support to the elderly. Local knowledge should be utilized when designing and delivering services. The key priority for older people is to maintain their indepenence and dignity. Having an adequate income to ensure financiall security to meet both daily and long-terms needs is essential to the wellbeing of older people.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Government department must work together in a strategic way to ensure the needs of older people in communities are understood and met. Statutory organizations must be proactive in conjenction with service users.Community based initiatives should be supported and developed. Proactive, preventative services which focus on independent living should be pursued.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>2176881A-10D3-4A82-BC3F-21AABA1369FF</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>54634dc5642874.71552162</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment,Healthcare,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.ofmdfmni.gov.uk/rural_ageing_in_ni___quality